#compdef vector-mcp-go
# ============================================================================
# vector-mcp-go - Vector/embedding MCP server with per-project codebase index
#                  (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : nilesh32236
# Upstream: https://github.com/nilesh32236/vector-mcp-go
#
# `vector-mcp-go` is a Model Context Protocol (MCP) server
# that indexes a project's codebase into a local vector store
# + exposes the index to AI coding agents as MCP tools
# (search by semantic similarity, rerank candidates, watch
# file changes for incremental re-index). Designed to run
# as a per-project daemon that any MCP-aware client (Claude
# Code, Cursor, Cline, Codex CLI, Gemini CLI, etc.) attaches
# to via a Unix-socket-backed stdio bridge.
#
# Architecture: a single Go process per project. The first
# instance for a given data-dir becomes the *master* (owns
# the embedding worker pool + vector store + file watcher);
# subsequent processes detect the master via a Unix socket
# (data-dir/daemon.sock) and become *workers* (forward MCP
# tool calls over the socket to the master). The embedding
# stack is ONNX Runtime + an HF tokenizer JSON config; the
# vector store is sqlite-vec for the on-disk index; the
# watcher is fsnotify for incremental re-indexing on file
# changes. Optional Prometheus + OpenTelemetry tracing
# integration via init-tracing-opentelemetry.
#
# Flags (Go stdlib `flag`):
#   -data-dir <dir>     - base directory for DB + models
#   -models-dir <dir>   - specific directory for ONNX models
#                         (defaults to <data-dir>/models)
#   -db-path <path>     - specific path for the vector DB
#                         (defaults to <data-dir>/db.sqlite)
#   -index              - run full codebase indexing + exit
#                         (initial scan; daemon mode handles
#                          incremental updates afterward)
#   -daemon             - run as background daemon (master
#                         worker) without MCP stdio server -
#                         useful for the long-lived index +
#                         watch loop
#   -version            - print version + build info
#   -h, --help          - print help
#
# The sugarme/tokenizer lane is built on `github.com/sugarme/
# tokenizer v0.3.0` (declared as a direct dep at upstream
# go.mod HEAD), the canonical Go port of huggingface/
# tokenizers by Truong Mai (github.com/sugarme/tokenizer,
# 200+ stars). sugarme/tokenizer is a *line-by-line port* of
# the Rust huggingface/tokenizers crate to pure Go - it
# implements the same Byte-Pair-Encoding (BPE), WordPiece,
# Unigram, and Byte-Level-BPE algorithms with the same
# spec-bound output (a tokenizer.json file loads identically
# in either lane).
#
# An alternative Go lane exists - `daulet/tokenizers`, used
# by knights-analytics/hugot - which is CGo bindings to the
# Rust library rather than a pure-Go port. The pure-Go port
# has the Go ecosystem's preference for cross-compile-
# friendly distribution (no CGo, no C deps); the CGo
# bindings have access to the latest Rust-library features
# at the cost of breaking Go's cross-compile story. The
# split mirrors the Wasm-runtime axis (Axis 232) where
# wazero (pure-Go) won out over wasmtime-go (CGo) for the
# same reason.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 234 :: LLM tokenizers (BPE/WordPiece/Unigram/byte-BPE subword tokenization)
# Round 1401 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 234 (round-number landmark)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : huggingface/tokenizers       [R1400 _text-embeddings-router]
#   Go      : sugarme/tokenizer            [R1401 THIS FILE]
#                                            (alt: daulet/tokenizers via CGo)
#   TS/Node : @huggingface/tokenizers      [R1402 closing]
#
# sugarme/tokenizer is the rare "Go port of a Rust library"
# success story: pure-Go reimplementation that maintains
# bit-for-bit wire-format compatibility with the upstream
# Rust reference. The maintainability question - whether
# the port keeps pace with the upstream as new tokenizer
# algorithms ship - has been answered by the project's
# 6+ year track record of staying within 1-2 minor versions
# of huggingface/tokenizers.
#
# The Axis 234 pattern (canonical-library-as-spec-root,
# downstream lanes either port or bind) demonstrates the
# alternative to the more common pattern where each lane
# independently implements the same spec. Cross-lane
# interop in Axis 234 is unusually tight because all lanes
# trace back to the same source of truth.
# ============================================================================

_vector-mcp-go() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-data-dir[base directory for DB and models]:dir:_files -/' \
        '-models-dir[specific directory for ONNX models]:dir:_files -/' \
        '-db-path[specific path for the vector DB]:file:_files' \
        '-index[run full codebase indexing and exit]' \
        '-daemon[run as background daemon master (no MCP stdio server)]' \
        '-version[print version and exit]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_vector-mcp-go "$@"
